{"ts":"2026-06-26T07:52:16.968Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Adding useEffect & scan design**\n\nI've incorporated `useEffect` into `ClientWorkspace.tsx` and updated the imports accordingly. I'm now focused on the custom scanning animation; I'm planning to modify the button's appearance whenever `scanning` is true, as the first step in that animation's design.\n\n\n**Designing Scanning Panel**\n\nI'm now implementing the scanning panel design, aiming for a visually exciting animation. I've defined `scanStep` and `scanMessages` using `useState`. I'm also including `handleAuth` with a `setInterval` that manages `scanStep` to cycle through the messages during the scan. This will control the messaging to the user within the scan.\n\n\n**Implementing Scanner Element**\n\nI've integrated the scanner element, displaying it within the login form when the `scanning` state is true. I've included a glowing grid background and a dynamic, moving scanning line for visual effect. Additionally, I've added an animated target circle to complement this effect. Finally, I've updated the `handleAuth` to update both `setScanning` and `setAuthed` states.\n\n\n**Refining Visual Effects**\n\nI'm now refining the visual effects of the scanner element. I've integrated a glowing, spinning circle, with dynamic messaging controlled by `scanStep`. The messages update in sync with a spinning refresh icon. I'm aiming for a seamless and engaging scan animation.\n\n\n**Adding Telemetry Fluctuations**\n\nI'm now integrating telemetry data fluctuations into the analytics section. I've added state variables for CPU usage in different regions and an array for data points. A `useEffect` hook will be used to simulate fluctuating values, which is already set up and will be very helpful.\n\n\n**Simulating Telemetry Fluctuations**\n\nI've got the data fluctuation simulation working. I'm using `useEffect` with `setInterval` to update CPU usage and data points, with the range from 10-100. This handles the real-time simulation of changes. These fluctuations are region-specific, updating CPU values for various regions with unique logic to maintain realistic behavior.\n\n\n**Visualizing Load Metrics**\n\nI'm now integrating live system core load metrics into the display. I've designed the visual layout to present the simulated multi-regional kernel compute latency. This includes a clear presentation for CPU usage in Singapore and London. The color-coded indicators enhance the user's perception of the load status.\n\n\n**Visualizing CPU Metrics**\n\nI'm now focusing on visualizing the CPU metrics for New York. I'm dynamically displaying the CPU usage and plotting a sparkline graph within a dedicated panel. I'm also preparing to create the SVG path. I've designed horizontal guide lines in the container to enhance the sparkline's readability. I'm using gradient color to visualize the data.\n\n\n**Generating Sparkline Graphics**\n\nI'm now generating the sparkline graphics, focusing on filling the area and adding a stroke line. I'm dynamically creating SVG paths using the provided data points and the `linearGradient`. I'm using the sparkline to visualize the dynamic CPU usage data, making the information very easy to understand.\n\n\n**Refining Scalability with SVG**\n\nI'm optimizing the sparkline's scalability using `viewBox` and `preserveAspectRatio`. The `viewBox` attribute is now set for a precise width and height mapping.  I've verified the scaling behavior: the path automatically adjusts to container width, which is key. This is great.\n\n\n"}}
